value.value: A 5' UTR variant within an upstream open reading frame.

definition.value: Added 10 Apr 2024 at the request of Sarah Hunt (EBI). See GitHub Issue #647.

value.value: A sequence_feature with an extent greater than zero. A nucleotide region is composed of bases and a polypeptide region is composed of amino acids.
A 5' UTR variant where a stop codon in an upstream open reading frame is introduced, moved or lost.

definition.value: Added 10 Apr 2024 at the request of Sarah Hunt (EBI). See GitHub Issue #622.

value.value: A folded sequence.
A 5' UTR variant which disrupts the translation of an upstream open reading frame because the number of nucleotides inserted or deleted is not a multiple of three.

definition.value: Added 10 Apr 2024 at the request of Sarah Hunt (EBI). See GitHub Issue #621.

value.value: G-quartets are unusual nucleic acid structures consisting of a planar arrangement where each guanine is hydrogen bonded by hoogsteen pairing to another guanine in the quartet.
A 5' UTR variant where a premature stop codon is gained in an upstream open reading frame.

definition.value: Added 10 Apr 2024 at the request of Sarah Hunt (EBI). See GitHub Issue #624.
A coding exon that is not the most 3-prime or the most 5-prime in a given transcript.

value.value: A 5' UTR variant where the stop codon of an upstream open reading frame is lost.

definition.value: Added 10 Apr 2024 at the request of Sarah Hunt (EBI). See GitHub Issue #623.

value.value: The many tandem repeats (identical or related) of a short basic repeating unit; many have a base composition or other property different from the genome average that allows them to be separated from the bulk (main band) genomic DNA.
A region amplified by a PCR reaction.

definition.value: This term is mapped to MGED. This term is now located in OBI, with the following ID OBI_0000406.

value.value: One of a pair of sequencing reads in which the two members of the pair are related by originating at either end of a clone insert.

definition.value: A gene which, when transcribed, can be translated into a protein.
A gene which can be transcribed, but will not be translated into a protein.

value.value: The primary transcript of any one of several small cytoplasmic RNA molecules present in the cytoplasm and sometimes nucleus of a Eukaryote.
A small non coding RNA sequence, present in the cytoplasm.

A sequence element characteristic of some RNA polymerase II promoters required for the correct positioning of the polymerase for the start of transcription. Overlaps the TSS. The mammalian consensus sequence is YYAN(T|A)YY; the Drosophila consensus sequence is TCA(G|T)t(T|C). In each the A is at position +1 with respect to the TSS. Functionally similar to the TATA box element.

definition.value: Binds TAF1, TAF2.

value.value: A sequence element characteristic of some RNA polymerase II promoters; Positioned from +28 to +32 with respect to the TSS (+1). Experimental results suggest that the DPE acts in conjunction with the INR_motif to provide a binding site for TFIID in the absence of a TATA box to mediate transcription of TATA-less promoters. Consensus sequence (A|G)G(A|T)(C|T)(G|A|C).

definition.value: Binds TAF6, TAF9.

value.value: A sequence element characteristic of some RNA polymerase II promoters, located immediately upstream of some TATA box elements at -37 to -32 with respect to the TSS (+1). Consensus sequence is (G|C)(G|C)(G|A)CGCC. Binds TFIIB.

definition.value: Binds TFIIB.

value.value: A sequence element characteristic of the promoters of snRNA genes transcribed by RNA polymerase II or by RNA polymerase III. Located between -45 and -60 relative to the TSS. The human PSE_motif consensus sequence is TCACCNTNA(C|G)TNAAAAG(T|G). The basal transcription factor, snRNA-activating protein complex (SNAPc), binds the PSE_motif and is required for the transcription of both RNA polymerase II and III transcribed small-nuclear RNA genes.
A group of loci that can be grouped in a linear order representing the different degrees of linkage among the genes concerned.

A region of double stranded RNA where the bases do not conform to WC base pairing. The loop is closed on both sides by canonical base pairing. If the interruption to base pairing occurs on one strand only, it is known as a bulge.
An internal RNA loop where one of the strands includes more bases than the corresponding region on the other strand.
A region forming a motif, composed of adenines, where the minor groove edges are inserted into the minor groove of another helix.
The kink turn (K-turn) is an RNA structural motif that creates a sharp (~120 degree) bend between two continuous helices.
A loop in ribosomal RNA containing the sites of attack for ricin and sarcin.
An internal RNA loop where the extent of the loop on both stands is the same size.

definition.value: Two bases paired opposite each other by hydrogen bonds creating a secondary structure.

value.value: The canonical base pair, where two bases interact via WC edges, with glycosidic bonds oriented cis relative to the axis of orientation.
A type of non-canonical base-pairing.
DNA or RNA molecules that have been selected from random pools based on their ability to bind other molecules.
DNA molecules that have been selected from random pools based on their ability to bind other molecules.
RNA molecules that have been selected from random pools based on their ability to bind other molecules.

Morpholino oligos are synthesized from four different Morpholino subunits, each of which contains one of the four genetic bases (A, C, G, T) linked to a 6-membered morpholine ring. Eighteen to 25 subunits of these four subunit types are joined in a specific order by non-ionic phosphorodiamidate intersubunit linkages to give a Morpholino.

A riboswitch is a part of an mRNA that can act as a direct sensor of small molecules to control their own expression. A riboswitch is a cis element in the 5' end of an mRNA, that acts as a direct sensor of metabolites.
A DNA region that is required for the binding of chromatin to the nuclear matrix.
A DNA region that includes DNAse hypersensitive sites located near a gene that confers the high-level, position-independent, and copy number-dependent expression to that gene.

definition.value: Definition updated Nov 10 2020, Colin Logie from GREEKC helped us realize that LCRs can also be located 3' to a gene.

value.value: A part of a match, for example an hsp from blast is a match_part.
